{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"853e990b-acc1-45a8-9a1c-2ba3e766ca40","content":"Yes, the tutorial's approach is **mostly correct** for .NET MAUI on .NET 10. Here's the breakdown:\n\n### `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` ✅\nThis is the standard iOS platform-specific that adjusts the page's content area to respect safe area insets (notch, home indicator, etc.). In your XAML:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\nOr in C#:\n```csharp\nOn<iOS>().SetUseSafeArea(true);\n```\n\nThis remains the recommended approach in .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\n### `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` ✅\nThis lets a specific layout extend **beyond** the safe area — perfect for full-bleed background images while the rest of the content stays safe. Example:\n\n```xml\n<Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\n### Recommended pattern\nCombine both: use `UseSafeArea` on the page, then `IgnoreSafeArea` only on the container holding your background image. This keeps text/buttons away from the notch while the background fills the screen.\n\n> **Tip:** Always verify against the [official .NET MAUI docs](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/maui/) for any .NET 10 preview-to-GA changes, as APIs can shift during the preview cycle.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e7ab4366-0aa5-4860-8b90-0c29f0f38a25","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for background images\n\nLet me check what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs, particularly any changes in .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved:\n\n- `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was a Xamarin.Forms-era platform-specific. In .NET MAUI, safe area insets are handled differently.\n\n\n- In .NET MAUI, `Page.UseSafeArea` still exists as an iOS platform-specific, though safe areas are now handled more automatically by default, and you can also control padding on the page directly. For .NET 10 specifically, I should verify if there have been any additional changes to how these properties work or if there are newer approaches recommended. I'm settling on `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` as the standard approach and `IgnoreSafeArea` as a property for layouts that need to extend beyond the safe area, both of which should work in .NET 10 MAUI. I'm less certain about whether there have been any recent deprecations or API changes, so I should acknowledge that uncertainty rather than guess.","outputTokens":1155,"requestId":"9BD5:12ABA3:632E2E1:6E7E851:69EC11FE"},"id":"d290c2d8-a27f-42e9-843f-af510288385e","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:00:04.152Z","parentId":"74a31aaf-368d-4054-9aeb-4772ecbb49ed"}
